Since the introduction of the Sustainable Development Goals in 2015 by the United Nations (UN), many countries worldwide, their citizens, and institutions have been engaged in drawing policies that concern environmental, social, and human development (F. C. M. García et al., 2021). The UN Sustainable Development Goals highlight essential issues faced by people worldwide. When these goals are orderly tackled, the world will be safe (United Nations, 2020). There are 17 SDGs (see Fig. 1
                     ), each covering a critical field of sustainable development defined by many societal, economic, or ecological metrics (Lamichhane et al., 2021). It is reported that the economy-related targets such as SDG-8, SDG-9, and SDG-12 are close to being realized. A lot of improvement is still needed to realize targets such as SDG-4, SDG-11, and SDG-13 (Halkos and Gkampoura, 2021). China has integrated the 2030 Agenda in the 13th Five-Year Plan, launched in January 2016 to realize the SDGs. The country has established an inter-agency coordination mechanism involving 45 government departments. According to their administrative responsibilities, the 17 goals and 169 targets have been divided and assigned to different departments (Jiang, 2020). Table 1

                      presents the specific targets set in China related to solid waste management, clean energy, and climate action to respond to the SDGs and the respective department to take control.
